# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dependency-pinning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **coupling** is the degree of interdependence between software modules, a measure of how closely connected two routines or modules are, and the strength of the relationships between modules.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling is not binary but multi-dimensional.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling is usually contrasted with cohesion.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling often correlates with high cohesion, and vice versa.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling is often thought to be a sign of a well-structured computer system and a good design, and when combined with high cohesion, supports the general goals of high readability and maintainability.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] The software quality metrics of coupling and cohesion were invented by Larry Constantine in the late 1960s as part of a structured design, based on characteristics of “good” programming practices that reduced maintenance and modification costs.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Structured design, including cohesion and coupling, were published in the article *Stevens, Myers & Constantine* (1974) and the book *Yourdon & Constantine* (1979), and the latter subsequently became standard terms.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling and cohesion are terms which occur together very frequently.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling refers to the interdependencies between modules, while cohesion describes how related the functions within a single module are.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Low cohesion implies that a given module performs tasks which are not very related to each other and hence can create problems as the module becomes large.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling can be "low" (also "loose" and "weak") or "high" (also "tight" and "strong").
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] A module here refers to a subroutine of any kind, i.e. a set of one or more statements having a name and preferably its own set of variable names.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Content coupling is said to occur when one module uses the code of another module, for instance a branch.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Common coupling is said to occur when several modules have access to the same global data.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] But it can lead to uncontrolled error propagation and unforeseen side-effects when changes are made.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] This is basically related to the communication to external tools and devices.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Control coupling is one module controlling the flow of another, by passing it information on what to do (e.g., passing a what-to-do flag).
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] and use only parts of it, possibly different parts (e.g., passing a whole record to a function that needs only one field of it).
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] In this situation, a modification in a field that a module does not need may lead to changing the way the module reads the record.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] , even if they do not utilize the modified attribute.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Data coupling occurs when modules share data through, for example, parameters.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Each datum is an elementary piece, and these are the only data shared (e.g., passing an integer to a function that computes a square root).
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Describes the relationship between a child and its parent.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] The child is connected to its parent, but the parent is not connected to the child.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] It is when two actions are bundled together into one module just because they happen to occur at the same time.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] In recent work various other coupling concepts have been investigated and used as indicators for different modularization principles used in practice.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] The goal of defining and measuring this type of coupling is to provide a run-time evaluation of a software system.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] It has been argued that static coupling metrics lose precision when dealing with an intensive use of dynamic binding or inheritance.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] In the attempt to solve this issue, dynamic coupling measures have been taken into account.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] This kind of a coupling metric considers the conceptual similarities between software entities using, for example, comments and identifiers and relying on techniques such as latent semantic indexing (LSI).
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Assembly of modules might require more effort and/or time due to the increased inter-module dependency.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] A particular module might be harder to reuse and/or test because dependent modules must be included.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Longer messages require more CPU and memory to produce.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, message length must be minimized and message meaning must be maximized.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Since a message must be transmitted in full to retain its complete meaning, message transmission must be optimized.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Longer messages require more CPU and memory to transmit and receive.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Also, when necessary, receivers must reassemble a message into its original state to completely receive it.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Hence, to optimize runtime performance, message length must be minimized and message meaning must be maximized.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Message protocols and messages themselves often contain extra information (i.e., packet, structure, definition and language information).
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Hence, the receiver often needs to translate a message into a more refined form by removing extra characters and structure information and/or by converting values from one type to another.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Any sort of translation increases CPU and/or memory overhead.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, message form and content must be reduced and refined to maximize its meaning and reduce translation.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] All messages must be interpreted by the receiver.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Simple messages such as integers might not require additional processing to be interpreted.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] messages require a parser and a string transformer for them to exhibit intended meanings.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] To optimize runtime performance, messages must be refined and reduced to minimize interpretation overhead.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] One approach to decreasing coupling is functional design, which seeks to limit the responsibilities of modules along functionality.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Low coupling refers to a relationship in which one module interacts with another module through a simple and stable interface and does not need to be concerned with the other module's internal implementation (see Information Hiding).
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Systems such as CORBA or COM allow objects to communicate with each other without having to know anything about the other object's implementation.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Both of these systems even allow for objects to communicate with objects written in other languages.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling describes the degree and nature of dependency between software components, focusing on what they share (e.g., data, control flow, technology) and how tightly they are bound.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] It evaluates two key dimensions: strength, which measures how difficult it is to change the dependency, and scope (or visibility), which indicates how widely the dependency is exposed across modules or boundaries.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Traditional coupling types typically include content coupling, common coupling, control coupling, stamp coupling, external coupling, and data coupling.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence, introduced by Meilir Page-Jones, provides a systematic framework for analyzing and measuring coupling dependencies.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence can be categorized into static (detectable at compile-time) and dynamic (detectable at runtime) forms.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Static connascence refers to compile-time dependencies, such as method signatures, while dynamic connascence refers to runtime dependencies, which can manifest in forms like connascence of timing, values, or algorithm.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Each coupling flavor can exhibit multiple types of connascence, a specific type, or, in rare cases, none at all, depending on how the dependency is implemented.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Common types of connascence include connascence of name, type, position, and meaning.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Certain coupling types naturally align with specific connascence types; for example, data coupling often involves connascence of name or type.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] However, not every combination of coupling and connascence is practically meaningful.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Dependencies relying on parameter order in a method signature demonstrate connascence of position, which is fragile and difficult to refactor because reordering parameters breaks the interface.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] In contrast, connascence of name, which relies on field or parameter names, is generally more resilient to change.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Connascence types themselves exhibit a natural hierarchy of strength, with connascence of name typically considered weaker than connascence of meaning.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Dependencies spanning module boundaries or distributed systems typically have higher coordination costs, increasing the difficulty of refactoring and propagating changes across distant boundaries.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Modern practices, such as dependency injection and interface-based programming, are often employed to reduce coupling strength and improve the maintainability of dependencies.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] While coupling identifies what is shared between components, connascence evaluates how those dependencies behave, how changes propagate, and how difficult they are to refactor.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Strength, locality, and degree are interrelated; dependencies with high strength, wide scope, and spanning distant boundaries are significantly harder to refactor and maintain.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Together, coupling provides a high-level overview of dependency relationships, while connascence offers a granular framework for analyzing dependency strength, locality, degree, and resilience to change, supporting the design of maintainable and robust systems.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] Coupling in Software Engineering describes a version of metrics associated with this concept.
[src:dependency-pinning/coupling-computer-programming] `Coupling(C)` makes the value larger the more coupled the module is.
[src:dependency-pinning/dependency-hell] The dependency issue arises when several packages have dependencies on the same *shared* packages or libraries, but they depend on different and incompatible versions of the shared packages.
[src:dependency-pinning/dependency-hell] If the shared package or library can only be installed in a single version, the user may need to address the problem by obtaining newer or older versions of the dependent packages.
[src:dependency-pinning/dependency-hell] This, in turn, may break other dependencies and push the problem to another set of packages.
