[src:dependency-pinning/dependency-hell] On specific computing platforms, *dependency hell* often goes by a local specific name, generally the name of components.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:dependency-pinning/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:dependency-pinning/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Reproducible builds can act as part of a chain of trust; the source code can be signed, and deterministic compilation can prove that the binary was compiled from trusted source code.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Verified reproducible builds provide a strong countermeasure against attacks where binaries do not match their source code, e.g., because an attacker has inserted malicious code into a binary.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] This is a relevant attack; attackers sometimes attack binaries but not the source code, e.g., because they can only change the distributed binary or to evade detection since it is the source code that developers normally review and modify.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] In a survey of 17 experts, reproducible builds had a very high utility rating from 58.8% participants, but also a high-cost rating from 70.6%.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Various efforts are being made to modify software development tools to reduce these costs.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] For the compilation process to be deterministic, the input to the compiler must be the same, regardless of the build environment used.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] This typically involves normalizing variables that may change, such as order of input files, timestamps, locales, and paths.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Additionally, the compilers must not introduce non-determinism themselves.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] This sometimes happens when using hash tables with a random hash seed value.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] It can also happen when using the address of variables because that varies from address space layout randomization (ASLR).
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Build systems, such as Bazel, GNU Guix, and Gitian, can be used to automate deterministic build processes.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] The GNU Project used reproducible builds in the early 1990s.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Changelogs from 1992 indicate the ongoing effort.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] One of the older projects to promote reproducible builds is the Bitcoin project with Gitian, and later, GNU Guix.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] In 2013, the Tor (anonymity network) project started using Gitian for their reproducible builds.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] Starting in 2011, a reproducible Java build system was developed for the decentralized peer-to-peer FOSS project DirectDemocracyP2P.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] The concepts of the system's application to automated updates recommendation support was first presented in April 2013 at Decentralized Coordination.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] A treatise focusing on the implementation details of the reproducible Java compilation tool itself was published in 2015.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] In July 2013, the Debian project started implementing reproducible builds across its entire package archive.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] By July 2017, more than 90% of the packages in the repository were proven to build reproducibly.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] In November 2018, the Reproducible Builds project joined the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] F-Droid uses reproducible builds to provide a guarantee that distributed APKs use the claimed free source code.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] The Tails portable operating system uses reproducible builds and explains to others how to verify their distribution.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] NixOS claims 100% build reproducibility as of June 2021 for their minimal ISO releases.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] As of May 2020, Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] As of March 2025, Debian live images for Bookworm are reproducible.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] The FreeBSD operating system builds reproducibly and without root access since October 2025.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] According to the Reproducible Builds project, timestamps are "the biggest source of reproducibility issues.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] In some cases other changes must be made to make a build process reproducible.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] For example, some data structures do not guarantee a stable order in each execution.
[src:dependency-pinning/reproducible-builds] A typical solution is to modify the build process to specify a sorted output from those structures.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.8.1, 1.9.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.8, 1.81, 1.82.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added or for marketing purposes.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Version numbers are often used to identify copies of a software product and compare them against another copy in a collaborative version control system.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Within software development teams, version control is used to keep track of incrementally-different versions of information in order to be able to roll any changes back.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Modern computer software is often tracked using two different software versioning schemes: an internal version number, which may be incremented many times in a single day, and a release version, which typically changes far less often.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Historically, file numbers were especially used in public administration and corporations to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This practice was introduced to computer files for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX file system for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a standardized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy, which is particularly useful when using software libraries, frameworks, and command-line applications.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] File numbers were used especially in public administration, as well as companies, to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For computer files this practice was introduced for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX filesystem for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Later lists of files including their versions were added, and dependencies amongst them.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Linux distributions like Debian, with its dpkg, early on created package management software which could resolve dependencies between their packages.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Debian's first try was that a package knew other packages which depended on it.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] From 1994 on this idea was inverted, so a package that knew the packages it needed.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] When installing a package, dependency resolution was used to automatically calculate the packages needed as well, and install them with the desired package.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] To facilitate upgrades, minimum package versions were introduced.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Thus the numbering scheme needed to tell which version was newer than the required one.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In sequence-based software versioning schemes, each software release is assigned a unique identifier that consists of one or more sequences of numbers or letters.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This is the extent of the commonality; schemes vary widely in areas such as the number of sequences, the attribution of meaning to individual sequences, and the means of incrementing the sequences.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In some schemes, sequence-based identifiers are used to convey the significance of changes between releases.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Semantic versioning (aka SemVer) is a widely adopted version scheme that encodes a version by a three-part version number (Major.Minor.Patch), an optional prerelease tag, and an optional build meta tag.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In this scheme, risk and functionality are the measures of significance.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Breaking changes are indicated by increasing the major number (high risk); new, non-breaking features increment the minor number (medium risk); and all other non-breaking changes increment the patch number (lowest risk).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The presence of a prerelease tag (-alpha, -beta) indicates substantial risk, as does a major number of zero (0.y.z), which is used to indicate a work-in-progress that may contain any level of potentially breaking changes (highest risk).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] As an example of inferring compatibility from a SemVer version, software which relies on version 2.1.5 of an API is compatible with version 2.2.3, but not necessarily with 3.2.4.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A fourth number may also be used to denote the software build, as was the case for Adobe Flash.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some companies also include the build date and letters and other characters, such as Lotus 1-2-3 Release 1a.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added, but are not enough to warrant incrementing a major version number; for example, Internet Explorer 5 from 5.1 to 5.5 or Adobe Photoshop 5 to 5.5.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A different approach is to use the *major* and *minor* numbers along with an alphanumeric string denoting the release type, e.g.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A software release train using this approach might look like 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9 → 1.0b1, 1.0b2 (with some fixes), 1.0b3 (with more fixes) → 1.0rc1 (if it is stable *enough*), 1.0rc2 (if more bugs are found) → 1.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] It is a common practice in this scheme to lock out new features and breaking changes during the release candidate phases and, for some teams, even betas are locked down to bug fixes only, to ensure convergence on the target release.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Again, in these examples, the definition of what constitutes a "major" as opposed to a "minor" change is entirely subjective and up to the author, as is what defines a "build", or how a "revision" differs from a "minor" change.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] : The most recent interface number that the library implements.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] : The implementation number of the current interface.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] : The difference between the newest and oldest interfaces that the library implements.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] : others may use a different meaning or simply ignore it.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A similar problem of relative change significance and versioning nomenclature exists in book publishing, where edition numbers or names can be chosen based on varying criteria.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In most proprietary software, the first released version of a software product has version 1.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some projects use the major version number to indicate incompatible releases.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Two examples are Apache Portable Runtime (APR) and the FarCry CMS.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Often programmers write new software to be backward compatible.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For example, IBM z/OS is designed to work properly with 3 consecutive major versions of the operating system running in the same sysplex.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This enables people who run a high availability computer cluster to keep most of the computers up and running while one machine at a time is shut down, upgraded, and restored to service.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Often packet headers and file format include a version number – sometimes the same as the version number of the software that wrote it; other times a "protocol version number" independent of the software version number.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The code to handle old deprecated protocols and file formats is often seen as cruft.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Software in the experimental stage (alpha or beta) often uses a zero in the first ("major") position of the sequence to designate its status.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] However, this scheme is only useful for the early stages, not for upcoming releases with established software where the version number has already progressed past 0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The two purely numeric forms remove the special logic required to handle the comparison of "alpha < beta < rc < no prefix" as found in semantic versioning, at the cost of clarity.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.7.0, 1.8.0, 1.8.1, 1.9.0, 1.10.0, 1.11.0, 1.11.1, 1.11.2, and so on.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.7, 1.8, 1.81, 1.82, 1.9, etc.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Decimal versions were common in the 1980s, for example with NetWare, DOS, and Microsoft Windows, but even in the 2000s have been for example used by Opera and Movable Type.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In the decimal scheme, 1.81 is the minor version following 1.8, while maintenance releases (i.e. bug fixes only) may be denoted with an alphabetic suffix, such as 1.81a or 1.81b.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The standard GNU version numbering scheme is major.minor.revision, but Emacs is a notable example using another scheme where the major number (1) was dropped and a *user site* revision was added which is always zero in original Emacs packages but increased by distributors.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Similarly, Debian package numbers are prefixed with an optional "epoch", which is used to allow the versioning scheme to be changed.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In some cases, developers may decide to reset the major version number.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This is sometimes used to denote a new development phase being released.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For example, *Minecraft* Alpha ran from version 1.0.0 to 1.2.6, and when Beta was released, it reset the major version number and ran from 1.0 to 1.8.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Once the game was fully released, the major version number again reset to 1.0.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some projects use negative version numbers.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] One example is the SmartEiffel compiler which started from −1.0 and counted upwards to 0.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] To ease sorting, some software packages represent each component of the *major.minor.release* scheme with a fixed width.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Perl represents its version numbers as a floating-point number; for example, Perl's 5.8.7 release can also be represented as 5.008007.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This allows a theoretical version of 5.8.10 to be represented as 5.008010.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Other software packages pack each segment into a fixed bit width; for example, on Microsoft Windows, version number 6.3.9600.16384 would be represented as hexadecimal 0x0006000325804000.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The floating-point scheme breaks down if any segment of the version number exceeds 999; a packed-binary scheme employing 16 bits apiece breaks down after 65535.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Between the 1.0 and the 2.6.x series, the Linux kernel used odd minor version numbers to denote development releases and even minor version numbers to denote stable releases.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For example, Linux 2.3 was a development family of the second major design of the Linux kernel, and Linux 2.4 was the stable release family that Linux 2.3 matured into.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] After the minor version number in the Linux kernel is the release number, in ascending order; for example, Linux 2.4.0 → Linux 2.4.22.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Since the 2004 release of the 2.6 kernel, Linux no longer uses this system, and has a much shorter release cycle.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The same odd-even system is used by some other software with long release cycles, such as Node.js up to version 0.12 as well as WineHQ.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Many projects use a date-based versioning scheme called **Calendar Versioning** (aka **CalVer**).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Ubuntu is one example of a project using calendar versioning; Ubuntu 18.04, for example, was released in April 2018.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This has the advantage of being easily relatable to development schedules and support timelines.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some video games also use date as versioning, for example the arcade game *Street Fighter EX*.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] At startup it displays the version number as a date plus a region code, for example *961219 ASIA*.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] When using dates in versioning, for instance, file names, it is common to use the ISO 8601 scheme *YYYY-MM-DD*, as this is easily string-sorted in increasing or decreasing order.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The Wine project formerly used a date versioning scheme, which used the year followed by the month followed by the day of the release; for example, "Wine 20040505".
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The earliest development builds of *Minecraft* had a similar version formatting, but instead used DDHHMM, for example rd-131655 was created on the 13th (of May 2009) at 16:21.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Microsoft Office build numbers are an encoded date: the first two digits indicate the number of months that have passed from the January of the year in which the project started (with each major Office release being a different project), while the last two digits indicate the day of that month.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] So 3419 is the 19th day of the 34th month after the month of January of the year the project started.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Other examples that identify versions by year include Adobe Illustrator 88 and WordPerfect Office 2003.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] When a year is used to denote version, it is generally for marketing purposes, and an actual version number also exists.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For example, Windows 95 is internally versioned as MS-DOS 7.00 and Windows 4.00; likewise, Windows 2000 is internally versioned as NT 5.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some software producers use different schemes to denote releases of their software.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The Debian project uses a major/minor versioning scheme for releases of its operating system but uses code names from the movie *Toy Story* during development to refer to stable, unstable, and testing releases.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] BLAG Linux and GNU features very large version numbers: major releases have numbers such as 50000 and 60000, while minor releases increase the number by 1 (e.g.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Alpha and beta releases are given decimal version numbers slightly less than the major release number, such as 19999.00071 for alpha 1 of version 20000, and 29999.50000 for beta 2 of version 30000.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Urbit uses *Kelvin versioning* (named after the absolute Kelvin temperature scale): software versions start at a high number and count down to version 0, at which point the software is considered finished and no further modifications are made.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In conjunction with the various versioning schemes listed above, a system for denoting prerelease versions is generally used, as the program makes its way through the stages of the software release life cycle.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Programs that are in an early stage are often called "alpha" software, after the first letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] After they mature but are not yet ready for release, they may be called "beta" software, after the second letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Generally alpha software is tested by developers only, while beta software is distributed for community testing.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some systems use numerical versions less than 1 (such as 0.9), to suggest their approach toward a final "1.0" release.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This is a common convention in open source software.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] However, if the prerelease version is for an existing software package (e.g. version 2.5), then an "a" or "alpha" may be appended to the version number.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] So the alpha version of the 2.5 release might be identified as 2.5a or 2.5.a.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Version numbers are used in practical terms by the consumer, or client, to identify or compare their copy of the software product against another copy, such as the newest version released by the developer.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For the programmer or company, versioning is often used on a revision-by-revision basis, where individual parts of the software are compared and contrasted with newer or older revisions of those same parts, often in a collaborative version control system.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a formalized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The purpose of such policies is to make it easier for other programmers to know when code changes are likely to break things they have written.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Such policies are especially important for software libraries and frameworks, but may also be very useful for command-line applications (which may be called from other applications) and for other applications (which may be scripted and/or extended by third parties).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A **software release train** is a form of software release schedule in which a number of distinct series of versioned software releases for multiple products are released as a number of different "trains" on a regular schedule.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Generally, for each product line, a number of different release trains are running at a given time, with each train moving from initial release to eventual maturity and retirement on a planned schedule.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Users may experiment with a newer release train before adopting it for production, allowing them to experiment with newer, "raw", releases early, while continuing to follow the previous train's point releases for their production systems prior to moving to the new release train as it becomes mature.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Cisco's IOS software platform used a release train schedule with many distinct trains for many years.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] More recently, a number of other platforms including Firefox and Fenix for Android, Eclipse, LibreOffice, Ubuntu, Fedora, Python, digiKam and VMware have adopted the release train model.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Software may have an "internal" version number which differs from the version number shown in the product name (and which typically follows version numbering rules more consistently).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Windows 10 was initially intended to be NT 6.4, as the earliest Technical Preview build shared to the public is numbered 6.4.9841.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] However, that did not last as the version of Windows 10 was quickly artificially increased to 10.0 to align with the commercial name, resulting in the first released version of the operating system being numbered 10.0.10240.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Note, however, that Windows NT is only on its fifth major revision, as its first release was numbered 3.1 (to match the then-current Windows release number) and the Windows 10 launching made a version leap from 6.3 to 10.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A relatively common practice is to make major jumps in version numbers for marketing reasons.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Sometimes software vendors just bypass the 1.0 release or quickly release a release with a subsequent version number because 1.0 software is considered by many customers too immature to trust with production deployments.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For example, as in the case of dBase II, a product is launched with a version number that implies that it is more mature than it is.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Other times version numbers are increased to match those of competitors.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This can be seen in many examples of product version numbering by Microsoft, America Online, Sun Solaris, Java Virtual Machine, SCO Unix, WordPerfect.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Microsoft Access jumped from version 2.0 to version 7.0, to match the version number of Microsoft Word.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Another example of keeping up with competitors is when Slackware Linux jumped from version 4 to version 7 in 1999.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This approach, panned by many because it breaks the semantic significance of the sections of the version number, has been adopted by an increasing number of vendors including Mozilla (for Firefox) and Google (for Google Chrome).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Sun also dropped the first digit for Solaris, where Solaris 2.8 (or 2.9) is referred to as Solaris 8 (or 9) in marketing materials.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A similar jump took place with the Asterisk open-source PBX construction kit in the early 2010s, whose project leads announced that the current version 1.8.x would soon be followed by version 10.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The free-software and open source communities tend to release software early and often.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Initial versions are numbers less than 1, with these 0.x version used to convey that the software is incomplete and not reliable enough for general release or usable in its current state.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Backward-incompatible changes are common with 0.x versions.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Version 1.0 is used as a major milestone, indicating that the software has at least all major features plus functions the developers wanted to get into that version, and is considered reliable enough for general release.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] A good example of this is the Linux kernel, which was first released as version 0.01 in 1991, and took until 1994 to reach version 1.0.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The developers of the arcade game emulator MAME do not ever intend to release a version 1.0 of the program because there will always be more arcade games to emulate and thus the project can never be truly completed.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Accordingly, version 0.99 was followed by version 0.100.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The Python Software Foundation has published PEP 440 – Version Identification and Dependency Specification, outlining their own flexible scheme, that defines an epoch segment, a release segment, prerelease and post-release segments and a development release segment.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] TeX has an idiosyncratic version numbering system, an unusual feature invented by its developer Donald Knuth.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Since version 3.1, updates have been indicated by adding an extra digit at the end, so that the version number asymptotically approaches the number π, so 3.14 effectively means 3.2 in semantic versioning.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] (This is a form of unary numbering; the version number is the number of digits.) Since 2021, the version number has been 3.141592653.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This is a reflection of TeX being very stable, and only minor updates are anticipated.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] TeX developer Donald Knuth has stated that the *"absolutely final change (to be made after [his] death)"* will be to change the version number to π, at which point all remaining bugs will become permanent features.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In a similar way, the version number of Metafont asymptotically approaches Euler's number, e.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Metafont was also devised by Donald Knuth as a companion to his TeX typesetting system.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] During the era of the classic Mac OS, minor version numbers rarely went beyond ".1".
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] When they did, they usually jumped straight to ".5", suggesting the release was "more significant".
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Thus, "8.5" was marketed as its own release, representing "Mac OS 8 and a half", and 8.6 effectively meant "8.5.1".
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Mac OS X departed from this trend, in large part because "X" (the Roman numeral for 10) was in the name of the product.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] As a result, all versions of OS X began with the number 10.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The first major release of OS X was given the version number 10.0, but the next major release was not 11.0.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Instead, it was numbered 10.1, followed by 10.2, 10.3, and so on for each subsequent major release.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Thus the 11th major version of OS X was labeled "10.10".
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Even though the "X" was dropped from the name as of macOS 10.12, this numbering scheme continued through macOS 10.15.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Under the "X"-based versioning scheme, the third number (instead of the second) denoted a minor release, and additional updates below this level, as well as updates to a given major version of OS X coming after the release of a new major version, were titled Supplemental Updates.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The Roman numeral X was concurrently leveraged for marketing purposes across multiple product lines.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Both QuickTime and Final Cut Pro jumped from version 7 directly to version 10, QuickTime X and Final Cut Pro X.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Like Mac OS X itself, the products were not upgrades to previous versions, but brand-new programs.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] As with OS X, major releases for these programs incremented the second digit and minor releases were denoted using a third digit.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The "X" was dropped from Final Cut's name with the release of macOS 11.0 (see below), and QuickTime's branding became moot when the framework was deprecated in favor of AVFoundation in 2011 (the program for playing QuickTime video was only named QuickTime Player from the start).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Apple's next macOS release, provisionally numbered 10.16, was officially announced as macOS 11 at WWDC in June 2020, and released in November 2020.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The following macOS version, macOS Monterey, was released in October 2021 and bumped its major version number to 12.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In June 2025, Apple announced an unified versioning scheme, using the year next to the release date, similar to model years in vehicles.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The versions that were released in the fall of 2025 are iOS 26, macOS 26, iPadOS 26, tvOS 26, watchOS 26 and visionOS 26.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The Microsoft Windows operating system was first labelled with standard version numbers for Windows 1.01 through Windows 3.2.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] After this Microsoft excluded the version number from the product name.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] For Windows 95 (version 4.0), Windows 98 (4.10) and Windows 2000 (5.0), year of the release was included in the product title.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] After Windows 2000, Microsoft created the Windows Server family which continued the year-based style with a difference: For minor releases, Microsoft suffixed "R2" to the title, e.g., Windows Server 2008 R2 (version 6.1).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] This style had remained consistent to this date.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The client versions of Windows however did not adopt a consistent style.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] First, they received names with arbitrary alphanumeric suffixes as with Windows Me (4.90), Windows XP (5.1), and Windows Vista (6.0).
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Then, once again Microsoft adopted incremental numbers in the title, but this time, they were not versioning numbers; the version numbers of Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 are respectively 6.1, 6.2 and 6.3.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] In Windows 10, the version number leaped to 10.0 and subsequent updates to the OS only incremented build number (which is date-based) and update build revision (UBR) number.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] The successor of Windows 10, Windows 11, was released on October 5, 2021.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Despite being named "11", the new Windows release did not bump its major version number to 11.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Instead, it stayed at the same version number of 10.0, used by Windows 10.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Some computer file systems, such as the OpenVMS Filesystem, also keep versions for files.
[src:dependency-pinning/software-versioning] Technical drawing and CAD software files may also use some kind of primitive versioning number to keep track of changes.
